    <p>
	<div style="clear:both;"></div><h2>Specialization is for Insects</h2>
<p>I&rsquo;ve become a regular reader of Oren Eini&rsquo;s blog, &ldquo;<em><a href="http://ayende.com/Blog/">Ayende @ Rahien</a></em>.&rdquo;&nbsp; Although I don&rsquo;t toil in the same developer space as Oren, I find that his introspective illustrations of methodology and technique yield little diamonds every day.&nbsp; His attention to testing is heart-warming.</p>
<p>Today, in a <a href="http://ayende.com/Blog/archive/2007/03/11/Specialization-Is-For-Insects.aspx">theme-titled post</a>, there is this great observation:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&ldquo;I expect to see a lot more work going into building non leaky abstractions in the future, and I think that we are getting better and better at it. Furthermore, I believe we will see a lot more emphasis on Not Surprising The Developer.&rdquo;</p></blockquote>
<p dir="ltr">I think it is more than that.&nbsp; We must stop Surprising the User (including the Developer special-case), for all of the same reasons.&nbsp; It seems to me that plugging-up the abstractions, and knowing how to have them fail&nbsp;appropriately&nbsp;when fail they must, is a perfect agenda for conquering the complexity that we have unleashed on the world in the name of mastering complexity.</p>
<p dir="ltr">There&rsquo;s a lot more in Oren&rsquo;s post and I recommend that you digest all of it (and then subscribe to his RSS feed).</p><div class="bjtags">Tags:  <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/orcmid">orcmid</a>, <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/Oren+Eini">Oren+Eini</a>, <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/Ayende+Rahien">Ayende+Rahien</a>, <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/abstractions">abstractions</a>, <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/software+testing">software+testing</a>, <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/software+fundamentals">software+fundamentals</a></div><div style="clear:both; padding-bottom:0.25em"></div>
    </p>
